metadata.name: On the sea, I ... #112
metadata.description:
Generative painting based on churning waves with floating buoys. Represented in three different media.

Features:
- Three drawing styles: "watercolor" 70%, "brush" 30%, or "block" 70%
- Warm white or blue waves
- Variable border and column sizes
- Number of columns
- Calm waves at the edges or center
- Color 80% or red 20% buoys
- Buoy drawing style, "watercolor" or "brush"

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

metadata.name: Orchard #355
metadata.description:
A natural media rendering of a fruit tree during one of the four seasons. Sometimes, you'll catch it at night - with lights strung on the tree!

The amount of color in spring and fall, snow in winter, fruit on and off the tree will all vary. There are four spring bloom palettes, four trunk colors, and seven types of fruit.

metadata.name: Meander River Plot v1 #97
metadata.description:
A river meandering over a noise-based landscape. A line is drawn either horizontally, vertically, or more rarely, a ring. Time progresses for 1,000 iterations as the line travels, bends, and splits. 

There is a lot of variation on the line quality - from thin and controlled, to chunky and chaotic. It's a lot of fun to watch it run and see where it ends up.

I've been experimenting with this algorithm for a long time and this is the most visually interesting variation so far.

metadata.name: Action Fields #346
metadata.description:
A generative painting based on abstract expressionism and the action paintings of Jackson Pollock.

Several different flow fields are used to create paths which are then painted in one of four different styles (pastel, paint, Pollock, black+gold). Additional features affect the background, path length + angles, level of detail, and mess (drips and splats). 

NOTES: 
- Some variations of the Pollock style may appear slightly different between browsers, but will render consistently in the same browser. 
- On slower devices, it may take some time to being drawing due to the background rendering.
- If you get a browser warning that the page is taking a long time, press continue.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1200x928px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 5,000 px. The ideal higher resolution is 2,000px.

metadata.name: Sound Swarm (Game) #4
metadata.description:
Sound Swarm is a simple rhythm-based game where you use your mouse or finger to control the white square to avoid hitting the colorful squares.

The relative energy of the music at any moment in time determines the spawn rate of the enemy squares, and is shown visually as a set of light-up radial sectors in the background.

To keep these NFTs small in file size, only 2 songs were added. This game can be played with more songs at 589designs.com

The two songs featured are Suno enhancements of old electronic songs I made, including a Tetris Theme Song remix as well as my own original piece.

Each NFT gets its own color scheme for the enemy squares and sector lights.

Works great in full screen.

metadata.name: Haiku For You #2
metadata.description:
---------------------------
Bionic minded;
Computers write poetry;
Creatively yours.
---------------------------

Every token generates a completely unique haiku!
No pre-generated lines, just a random, crazy poem for you!

Haikus follow this structure:
 - first line, 5 syllables
 - second line, 7 syllables
 - third line, 5 syllables

The program works by extracting types of words (singular nouns, connectives, adverbs, etc) from a database with words and syllables. It then uses rejection sampling combined with valid sentence structures to generate a collection of valid sentences with valid lengths.

Finally, it is all tied together and rendered in p5.js! 

[s] to save your haiku

metadata.name: Computational Poetry #4
metadata.description:
As I’ve transitioned to the e-reader ALL my reading highlights have been digitized. I saw this as an opportunity to take old things to generate new things.

In this art piece, I’ve used the p5.js and RiTa.js libraries in conjunction with my kindle highlights to generate haikus. Haikus are short poems that adhere to a 3 line, 5-7-5 syllable format.

I hope the paradox of purposeful distillation from my readings coupled with the randomness from the computation lends to some form of beauty and / or delight. (Spoiler - it’s mostly gibberish)

ENJOY! THE! PURPOSEFUL! RANDOMIZATION!

Some iterations of this drop have an interactive component to them, click or glide your mouse on the image to create some florals! Press S to save your image.

By @trp_chai

February 27 2023

Made with p5.js and <3
